1.To get the Python version you are using, you can use the following command in the command line:
python --version

2.To write a Python script that prints "Hello Python" on the screen directly in the command line, you can use the following code:
python
print("Hello Python")


3.To write a Python script and execute it from the command line, follow these steps:
Create a new file with a .py extension (e.g., script.py) and open it in a text editor.
Write your Python code in the file, for example:
python

print("Hello from a Python script file!")
Save the file.
Open the command line and navigate to the directory where the file is saved.
Execute the script using the following command:


python script.py
Replace script.py with the actual name of your file.

To print "Hello Python" on the screen using Visual Studio Code, you can create a new Python file and add the following code:
python
Copy code
print("Hello Python")
Save the file with a .py extension and click the "Run" button in Visual Studio Code to execute the script.

To print "Hello" on the first line and "Python" on the second line, you can use the following script:
python
Copy code
print("Hello")
print("Python")
To print "MySirG" on the screen, you can use the following script:
python
Copy code
print("MySirG")
To print "Teacher's Day" on the screen, you can use the following script:
python
Copy code
print("Teacher's Day")
To print the value of a variable containing your name, you can use the following script:
python
Copy code
name = "Your Name"
print(name)
Replace "Your Name" with your actual name.

To create variables to store your name, age, qualification, years of experience, and print them, you can use the following script:
python
Copy code
name = "Your Name"
age = 25
qualification = "Your Qualification"
years_of_experience = 5

print("Name:", name)
print("Age:", age)
print("Qualification:", qualification)
print("Years of Experience:", years_of_experience)
Replace the placeholders with your actual information.

To print the values of three variables, each in a new line, containing integer values, you can use the following script:
python
Copy code
variable1 = 10
variable2 = 20
variable3 = 30

print(variable1)
print(variable2)
print(variable3)
